abstract: Mr. Hastings’s best-known work, “Tom and Viv,” about the first marriage of T. S. Eliot, created a cultural brouhaha.
snippet: Mr. Hastings’s best-known work, “Tom and Viv,” about the first marriage of T. S. Eliot, created a cultural brouhaha.
lead_paragraph: Michael Hastings, a British playwright whose best-known work, “Tom and Viv,” about the first marriage of T. S. Eliot, created a cultural brouhaha over the appropriateness of fictionalizing the lives of real people, died on Nov. 19, at his home in London. He was 74.

abstract: Made prominent by his coverage of the Kennedy assassination, Mr. Wicker became Washington bureau chief for The New York Times and an iconoclastic columnist.
snippet: Made prominent by his coverage of the Kennedy assassination, Mr. Wicker became Washington bureau chief for The New York Times and an iconoclastic columnist.
lead_paragraph: Tom Wicker, one of postwar America’s most distinguished journalists, who wrote 20 books, covered the assassination of President John F. Kennedy for The New York Times and became the paper’s Washington bureau chief and an iconoclastic political columnist for 25 years, died on Friday at his home near Rochester, Vt. He was 85.

abstract: Ms. Delaney, whose play “A Taste of Honey” found success in the West End and on Broadway, was just 19 when the work was first performed.
snippet: Ms. Delaney, whose play “A Taste of Honey” found success in the West End and on Broadway, was just 19 when the work was first performed.
lead_paragraph: Shelagh Delaney, a British playwright and screenwriter who reached the height of her literary fame at 19 as an “angry young woman” — a characterization she detested — with the premiere of her play “A Taste of Honey,” died on Sunday at her daughter’s home in Suffolk, England. She was 72 and lived near Filey, a village in Yorkshire.

abstract: The market for Aboriginal works has suffered from the global financial crisis.
snippet: The market for Aboriginal works has suffered from the global financial crisis.
lead_paragraph: MELBOURNE — Five years ago, the market for Australian Aboriginal art was booming. A government standing committee valued the sector at up to 500 million Australian dollars, the opening of the Musée du Quai Branly in Paris helped foster international interest in the ancient style and works by prominent Aboriginal artists like Clifford Possum Tjapaltjarri sold for up to 2.4 million dollars at auction.
